Adding pet (and soon, drone) classes was a multi-month effort. If we cannot monetize our major development efforts, we have to stop making games.  Email me at atrese@gmail.com if you have any questions.

First off great game, an early Trese effort and it shows in some of the mechanics, but considering that its open world and not story driven, its a very interesting piece.  Secondly, a couple issues that I've had since picking this up again after a couple years away:  1) Having some issues at Riccos Boat Serve - after selecting dialogue to get transport his dialogue box shows up but no options to continue or back out.  2) Less concerning (don't have to reset), but still annoying and more frequent (don't use the boats much once I have enough taxi drivers), is that when I select missions from connectors sometimes I get a Cyber Knights Stopped Working error message and I'm kicked out of the mission list. I can go back in and select a mission fine - from a new/updated list of missions.   3) A tweak I'd be interested in is it would be nice if reputation wasn't lost so quickly by time passing. If reputation gains were lowered a bit per quest and/or there were bigger penalties for working against a faction that would be fine, but it's annoying to me that simply resting  and shopping or bar schmoozing or wandering a bit can drop you by 2-3 missions worth of rep like nothing. It makes me feel like I have to scramble like a mad rat, always working against the clock, to build rep - rather than more simply being consistent and faithful with one group to climb their ladder. It could take the same or more time/missions without the current extreme of a two-steps-forward-one step-back, grind-against-the-clock mechanic. Also it would be easier to keep rep up with two different factions, as long as you didn't actively work against your friends and did some big jobs for them from time to time.

I've been playing this off and on for years and I must say I'm still immensely disappointed with the insane difficulty spike of the random encounters. I understand that each faction differs in strength, but getting mobbed by eight full strength mars enforcers without having any heat and moderate rep greatly upsets me, especially with how long it takes me to get to the mars zones. Decent game with unscaled random mechanics and massively widespread weapon placement makes for irritating travelling even with 200+ xp

Constant updates and fixes, with constantly evolving content. The tutorial is friendly for newbies and trusts the player to be intelligent enough when to stop spoon feeding information. Then once the tutorial area ends you feel badass enough to take on a few tough missions... until a killer hund takes you down. The climb to the top is hard but the game design and the writing makes you want to be smarter and try harder. Great value for the quality and the quality of the content. EDIT: Played on the tablet and the menus aren't scaled for the screen real estate. It's still a great game (if you can stomach the weird UI if you're playing on a tablet). It's not as or as taken care of as the Star Trader series but this is still among the top 10 or 20 mobile games you will ever play. EVER.

Cory watches responses and addresses issues when they are reported, often by the next update. Most developers are unreachable and unresponsive. These guys are passionate about their games and want to make them better.

Another very good rpg from serial top developer Cory Trese. A cyber-punk near future thriller played out in a climate of mega corporation control, human cybernetic implants and cyber-hacking. A terrific and stylish neo-noir thriller with well implimented controls, challenging turn-based combat, easy to learn rules making the game simple enough to pick up and play for novices, but challenging enough to cater for rpg veterans alike. An ever-present game among the constantly changing catalogue on my phone. I loved this game so much i bought the Elite version to support this passionate independant developer. Cory Trese consistantly update and improve their games regularly too. Top game, top developer, top fun...guarenteed. 5 stars!!

Whether hacking, fighting or simply delivering information from one map to another, after an unreal 250+ updates, there's simply nothing else like it!

It is heavily inspired by the Sega Genesis game called Shadow run, which was based on a popular tabletop RPG.
If you enjoyed Shadowrun on the SEGA Genesis, then this game is right up your alley.  Also it is constantly updated with bug fixes and new features.

replyContent: @jesse - sorry about McCougan.  He will be removed from the game for the next update.  Since he was first accidentally added as a dead-end, we've added a full story, rewrote the jobs system, added the Encounters system, added the pet system (Hunds and Drones coming), as well as adding 3 more ladder connectors. content: The Bros Trese have again blown my mind with a fun and simple game. It is worth every penny paid for it. I am looking forward to this game reaching its full potential. Keep up the great work guys!  UPDATE 3/31/2015  There's not enough cools words to describe this game and how much it has grown in the past few years I've been playing it. If you love cyberpunk settings and trying to survive in a world that's out to get you, then this is your game of choice. Will you hold on to what humanity you have left or go full cyborg conversion and become an almost god like war machine. replyContent: @matthew - thanks for the feedback. CK's been on GPlay for 3 years and had over 250 updates. We will continue to improve both Elite and Free. Adding pet (and soon, drone) classes was a multi-month effort. If we cannot monetize our major development efforts, we have to stop making games.  Email me at atrese@gmail.com if you have any questions.

replyContent: @matt - thanks for the feedback!  Over 3 years and 250 updates, we have made major improvements to ever system of Cyber Knights. replyContent: @user - As you mention, we've been updating CK since 2011.  We've dropped over 250 update actually, and will continue to do so. It's all too easy to get drawn into this game.  The interface, artwork, text, and music all set the perfect mood.  Even the retro graphics (which you can tell are lovingly drawn by the devs) contribute the setting, which is futuristic yet nostalgic. Playability is top-notch, and what's really great is it allows you to use your imagination to fill in details and plot.  I had a contract to kill a Fennian shop owner, for example, but when I got there I found I just couldn't do it (she was too charming).  My character changed his allegiances then and there.  The devs are very responsive and are constantly making improvements to the game.  I appreciate that the free version is truly free (no ads, no nagging), but I found it a bargain to upgrade to Elite.  Well worth the money, and well worth supporting.

replyContent: @david - sorry that you encountered so many bugs.  CK is stable on all of our test devices, so if you'd like to work with us to resolve these bugs, we are very happy to help.  Also, we are also happy to offer you a refund.  Just contact me at atrese@gmail.com about either option!

**********The game is a nice retro turn based RPG and its cheap to boot. Reminds of of early Shadowrun games.  **********The game needs a lot of work. It crashes my Milestone X regularly. The gameplay sometimes feels clunky, and its not intuitive. These points are getting resolved as CK is one of those games that is an active work in progress. Cory and Andrew Trese work constantly to improve the game. I am amazed by the level of communication that I've seen in the Proboards forums. These Indi. developers provide a level of direct interaction with their clients I have seldom, if ever, experienced. *********There is a story mode that provides a basic tutorial. There are dozens, if not hundreds, of different strategies to level up your characters. The game can be really challenging.   *********This game can only get better in time. If you're not a graphic's snub, I highly recommend this purchase.
